description.plain:
“One of LA’s smartest young voices” says the LA Times…which the artist suspects, may just be a covert way of saying LA is dumb. “Open” Mike Eagle wouldn’t terribly mind, being born and raised in Chicago where the painful winters and his uppity grandparents kept him inside as a youth.

He spent his formative years watching alternative music happen on MTV and hoping to one day be able to audition for the Native Tongues.

As a young adult after graduating with a degree in Psychology, he did the next best thing and moved to Los Angeles, joining the Project Blowed collective where he made music and toured with Busdriver, Aceyalone, Abstract Rude, Nocando and more. He’s also gained notoriety in the world of comedy by being invited by professional funny people (Paul F. Tompkins, Hannibal Buress, Matt Besser/UCB) to rap at their shows. He’d like to be rap’s Kurt Vonnegut but recognizes that he’d first have to create something as iconic as the four-stroke illustration of an anus. He practices by releasing rap albums that delight, entertain, and confuse.

songs.full_title: Legendary Iron Hood by Open Mike Eagle
songs.title: Legendary Iron Hood

description.plain:
This song introduces Iron Hood, the superhero/alter ego played by Open Mike Eagle, based in part on Juggernaut from the X-Men.

The Juggernaut alludes to the attitude of being a “tough guy”.  However, while the Juggernaut is tough he is still prone to mental weakness.  This mental weakness is embodied by the Juggernaut’s step brother, Charles Xavier, who is repeatedly brought up throughout the song.  While the Juggernaut may be physically strong he is still subject to telepathic attack from his step brother.  To compensate for his mental weakness the Juggernaut wears a helmet to protect him from Xavier.

This whole song can be thought of as an allegory for the mentality people are forced to have when growing up or living in tough communities.  To protect themselves people often don a “tough guy” persona when in reality they are still vulnerable to emotional pain.

From Open Mike Eagle’s Twitter:


this song is about a traumatized super hero that has a helmet made out of a radiator and the power to walk through gunfire.

songs.full_title: Brick Body Complex by Open Mike Eagle
songs.title: Brick Body Complex

description.plain:
“Brick Body Complex,” is a powerful and political proclamation of identity and strength told from the perspective of a project building and the individuals residing within it. Open Mike Eagle throughout the song construes the idea that he is as giant and as immovable as the old brick buildings, his lyrics standing together in uniformity like the wall of protesters seen within the music video.

The buildings Michael is referring to in this song are the public housing complex named Robert Taylor Homes — 28 high-rise buildings, 16 stories each that resided in South Side Chicago. Eagle spent a chunk of his childhood living in these projects alongside his aunt and cousins. In 2007, all of the buildings were torn down, displacing thousands of families from their homes, one third of which are still unaccounted for.

In the music video, Mike portrays a superhero character named “Iron Hood” who attempts to save the public housing project from being destroyed and replaced by commercial properties. He fights a masked man who seems to personify all of the people who had a hand in the buildings' destruction. In the end he loses, and is seemingly arrested by the police.

Throughout the song, Mike paints this picture of himself as a humongous 16-story building that is strong, sturdy, and indestructible. Seeing himself as a grandeur masterpiece that will live on forever, but sadly this is not the truth of the situation. In reality,  nothing is fair and everything eventually comes to an end… even the project buildings that he once resided in.

The “Brick Body Complex” seems to be the belief that you or the things that you hold dear are immortal when in reality things can be taken from you in the blink of an eye, fairly or otherwise.

songs.full_title: The Black Mirror Episode by Open Mike Eagle
songs.title: The Black Mirror Episode

description.plain:
As the chorus suggests, the song is about how a “Black Mirror episode ruined [Open Mike Eagle’s] marriage.” In a New York Times interview, Mike said:

It wasn’t like we called it quits that night, but we were watching an episode with this couple in it, and I don’t think we were able to come back from that.

Black Mirror is a science fiction anthology series streaming on Netflix since 2011. It’s about the positive and negative consequences of technology. The show is famous for exploring the various ways our own technological inventions could cause our downfall.



After repeatedly being asked about which episode he was talking about, Mike responded on Twitter:

I will never say what the black mirror episode is. tho quite a few people have guessed correctly.

While the show includes several episodes about relationships and people’s emotional issues, most fans speculate he’s talking about the season-one-finale, “The Entire History of You.” The episode takes place in a future where humans can get a memory implant that records everything they do, see, and hear.

songs.title_with_featured: No Selling (Uncle Butch Pretends It Don't Hurt)

description.plain:
In professional wrestling, selling your opponent’s moves is an important part of drawing the crowd into the match. Selling involves exaggerating the impact and pain inflicted by maneuvers to make the match believable and exciting. In this song, Mike references the act of “no selling” which is, as it sounds, not reacting to your opponent’s moves in a way that shows pain or weakness. In wrestling, this can show toughness in a particular character while being generally disrespectful to the other wrestler.

Mike uses this metaphor to play on the expectations of men to not show emotional vulnerability even when they are clearly in physical or psychological pain (eg. misspelling his name). Many cultures idealize the overly masculine man who maintains his composure through trauma. It’s likely that Mike wishes he could show more genuine emotion without fearing that it would come across as weakness.

According to Open Mike Eagle’s Twitter, “Uncle Butch” refers to his uncle that fought in Vietnam.

description.plain:
“Death Parade” was released October 13, 2020, in the lead up to Open Mike Eagle’s album Anime, Trauma, and Divorce, due to be released October 16. A video by animator Ben Clarkson was really in the same day.

The song is named after the anime Death Parade , about a bar where souls congregate after death. There they must participate in the Death Games for a chance at reincarnation, otherwise they will be sent to oblivion.  In a tweet, Mike called it his “modern favorite”.

https://img1.hulu.com/user/v3/artwork/4518d23e-60ec-4722-b5aa-bb3324b11bd3?base_image_bucket_name=image_manager&base_image=6c6bb887-86b3-4c69-8b78-49b85751bec0&region=US&format=jpeg&size=952x536

The lyrics of the song are about “the cycle of trauma,” and how, like the participants in the Death Games, we reincarnate that trauma on from one life to the next.

description.plain:
On this track, Open Mike Eagle provides an anthem for the headasses. “Headass” can be used as a generic insult but generally means someone who’s stupid, especially someone who is socially inept.

Shinji Ikari is the protagonist of Neon Genesis Evangelion, a cult classic manga and anime franchise. Shinji is a mech-pilot and a real headass. He is painfully introverted, nervous, and emotional. He even refused to pilot his mech, the Evangelion Unit-01, which became a meme.



Fellow mechi-pilot Asuka frequently insults Shinji with “anta baka!” roughly “you idiot!” or “idiot Shinji!” in English.

description.plain:
“Sweatpants Spiderman” finds Open Mike having to start over as he approaches middle-age. Newly divorced, he’s now trying to work out, dress fashionable, find a new place to live on an indie rapper’s budget, all while dealing with the emotional fallout of the divorce and his fortieth birthday fast approaching.

On the ATD release show livestream from Dynasty Typewriter, Mike referenced the 2018 film Spider-Man: Into the Spiderverse. One of the many spidermen we meet in that movie is Peter B. Parker, who is a depressed middle-aged man, separated from his wife. When we meet him, he’s looking kinda schlubby with his depression sweats over his spidersuit.

He dedicates the track to those affected by the decision made by the United States Department of Housing and Urban Development to destroy the last building of the homes in 2007. According to Pitchfork, by then over 11,000 people had occupied its 28 written off buildings.
